      "uuid": "b055cbd9-2060-4314-bf99-24d043d984e5",
      "text": " This appears to be a belt buckle with Church Slavonic text engraved on it. The text is from Psalm 143:9 (Psalm 142:9 in the Septuagint numbering used in Orthodox tradition):\n\n\"\u041e \u0413\u043e\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0434\u0438, \u043a \u0422\u0435\u0431\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0431\u0435\u0433\u0430\u044e, \u043d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u0438 \u043c\u044f \u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0438 \u0432\u043e\u043b\u044e \u0422\u0432\u043e\u044e\"\n\nIn modern transliteration, it reads approximately:\n\"Gdi i\u0394\u017dce Xrte B\u017ee moi, ne ostavh ma, i ne preda\u017ed du\u0161i moea vo isku\u0161enie, da ne udob\u016bta ma vrazi moi\"\n\nThis translates to English as:\n\"O Lord Jesus Christ my God, do not leave me, and do not deliver my soul to temptation, lest my enemies overcome me\"\n\nThis is a prayer for divine protection and guidance, commonly found on Orthodox Christian items like belt buckles, crosses, and other personal devotional objects. The Old Church Slavonic script and style is characteristic of traditional Russian Orthodox religious items.",
