    {
      "uuid": "95ae333a-4908-42c3-8b55-76c2538da3c0",
      "text": " This is the reverse side of the belt buckle, and it contains a Russian inscription that reads:\n\n**\u0417\u0410\u0429\u0418\u0422\u042a \u0422\u041e\u0422\u042a**\n**\u041a\u0422\u041e \u0421\u041e\u0412\u0415\u0420\u0428\u0418\u0422\u042a**\n**\u0413\u0420\u0462\u0425\u042a \u041f\u041e\u0414 \u041d\u0418\u041c\u042a**\n**\u0414\u041e \u041a\u041e\u041d\u0426\u0410**\n\nIn modern Russian orthography, this would be:\n\"\u0417\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442 \u0442\u043e\u0442 \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0448\u0438\u0442 \u0433\u0440\u0435\u0445 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u043d\u0438\u043c \u0434\u043e \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0430\"\n\nThis translates approximately to:\n\"Protected is the one who commits sin under it to the end\"\n\nHowever, this phrasing is somewhat unusual. It might be better interpreted as a warning or statement about the buckle's protective power, possibly meaning something like \"May it protect the one who [wears it/bears it] from sin until the end\" or could be a cautionary statement about accountability.\n\nThe use of the old orthography (with the hard sign \u042a at the end of words and the yat \u0462) confirms this is written in pre-1918 Russian style, consistent with traditional Orthodox religious items.",
